\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Work Order as Universal Requirement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The work order is the non-negotiable unit of accountability for all work performed by the Information Operations Department.
 A work order shall be created for every actionable task,
 without exception.
 This obligation applies regardless of whether the work is reactive or proactive,
 regardless of the channel through which the work was identified or requested,
 and regardless of the estimated duration or complexity of the task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
No IT work shall be performed,
 and no commitment to perform IT work shall be made,
 without an associated work order.
 The work order is the authoritative record of why a task was undertaken,
 who authorized it,
 what was done,
 and how it was resolved.
 The absence of a work order for completed work constitutes a documentation failure regardless of the operational outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The creation of a work order indicates that a request has been submitted to the IT Department for evaluation.
 It does not guarantee acceptance or execution.
 Work orders that fall outside the scope of IT responsibilities,
 that are submitted for Unsupported assets,
 or that cannot be resourced within current operational capacity shall be dispositioned in accordance with 
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Intake and Channel Routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The designated work order system (Redmine) is the authoritative intake channel for all service requests.
 Requests received through any other channel shall be routed to the work order system immediately,
 and in all cases no later than one (1) business hour following the receipt of the request or the initiation of the task,
 whichever occurs first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Walk-in requests
\series default
:
 When a County employee presents a request in person,
 the receiving IT staff member shall direct the requester to submit the request through the work order system.
 Where the requester is unable to do so,
 the IT staff member shall create the work order on the requester's behalf,
 ensuring that the Requested By field accurately identifies the actual requester in accordance with 
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Telephone requests
\series default
:
 Requests received by telephone shall be handled in the same manner as walk-in requests.
 The IT staff member shall create a work order concurrent with or immediately following the call and shall document the substance of the conversation in the work order notes in accordance with the out-of-band summarization requirements of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Email and informal digital communications:
 Requests received by email or other informal digital channels shall be routed to the work order system.
 The communication shall be summarized in the work order notes in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
In all cases,
 the work order is the record of the request.
 Channel acknowledgment to the requester —
 including verbal or informal confirmation —
 does not substitute for work order creation.
 IT staff shall not begin work on a request prior to work order creation except as provided under the emergency exception in Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 IT-Initiated Work Orders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department regularly initiates work that is not triggered by a user request.
 This includes infrastructure maintenance,
 proactive upgrades,
 compliance remediations,
 internal projects,
 and any other IT-driven activity that constitutes actionable work.
 All IT-initiated work requires a work order,
 and all IT-initiated work orders shall be designated using the Internal Project checkbox as defined in 
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The Internal Project designation is mandatory for all IT-initiated work without exception.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Authorization requirements for IT-initiated work orders are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Routine IT-initiated tasks
\series default
 —
 including scheduled maintenance,
 standard configuration updates,
 and minor proactive remediations —
 may be authorized by the assigned technician in accordance with their defined role authority under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The basis for authorization shall be documented in the work order at the time of creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Non-routine or significant IT-initiated tasks
\series default
 —
 including infrastructure changes,
 new deployments,
 system decommissions,
 or any task that materially alters the County's operational technology environment —
 shall be authorized by the Assistant IT Director or IT Director prior to work commencement.
 The authorizing official's name and the basis for authorization shall be documented in the work order before work begins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Project-level IT-initiated work
\series default
 —
 as determined by scope,
 resource requirements,
 or duration —
 shall additionally be subject to the project management requirements of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.14"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Triage and Authorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All work orders shall undergo IT-side triage prior to the commencement of active work,
 in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.3.
 Triage confirms or reclassifies the severity level,
 validates scope,
 identifies the applicable asset support classification,
 and initiates or queues the appropriate response.
 Work shall not begin on a work order until triage is complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Where a submitted work order lacks sufficient information to complete triage,
 the assigned technician or queue reviewer shall document the triage attempt,
 specify the information required,
 and notify the requester that more information is needed.
 The work order shall remain in Queued status for the duration of this pending information period.
 Service level clocks shall be paused and shall resume upon receipt of the required information from the requester.
 Work orders that remain without requester response for five (5) consecutive business days shall be closed by the assigned technician or queue reviewer,
 with closure rationale documented in the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Waiting for User status,
 as defined in 
\series bold
Appendix 
